I am impressed that they're not just doing a direct adaptation of The Crusades, The Renaissance, Piracy, American Revolution, French Revolution, or the Industrial Revolution.  It will be nice to see a new period for the Assassin's to be fighting in.    However, this could still suck.  I hope this movie is kick ass, and launches video game movies into the stratosphere like Comic Book movies.  Remember, comic book movies went through a time period where they all sucked too, and then someone figured out how to make awesome comic book movies.  Hopefully we get the same effect with Video Game movies!

text: Looks better than expected for a video game to movie ploy (they usually fail), and they have a handful of decent actors in there that actually may make this movie entertaining to watch. But I have to say, as many others here already have; poorly chosen music ruins the immersion.  For the line up of twats that are licking Kayne's boot heels and balls via blind fanatic fandom that doesn't allow for rational thought, its not that I'm insulting him or his music. (though I am certainly not a fan) It's just that his music and style and its effect on the whole time piece of this move trailer (historic) doesn't flow well at all...it's just another attempt to use familiar pop music to sell interest, not create an immersive movie experience visually backed by a fitting sound track.

text: Wow this looks like it may actually be one of the super-rare video game movie adaptations to be actually good.  Trailer impresses more than Warcraft trailer,.  I know a lot of people don't like the movie adaptation of Doom (which, to be fair, kinda missed the point) but when I saw it I came in with no expectations and what I got was a strong sci-fi action film with a great cast. Movie is criminally underrated and I think a lot of that is from people who (fairly) expected a movie about a lone badass killing a legion of demons.
author: Mark Samenfink

text: I love people rendering judgement before the movie even comes out, but I guess that's people today. Honestly the movie looks amazing, I, for the most part think the casting choice was good, do I feel Kanye was necessary? No, at least not the first part where he's actually rapping, but the part after that was good, and honestly people need to remember, this isn't the final soundtrack, at least as far as I know they haven't released who is going to compose the film so for those who enjoyed the Ezio's family instrumental or even Woodkid doing the soundtrack, just wait for the movie to come out.

text: From some reason I don't like it. The battle scenes seem to be to choreographed and due to that are not believable. In the game they fight quite elegantly yet their execution, moves and combos are quite believable which is why the game looks so cool. Here on the other hand it seems totally overdone. Also the whole take that he lives in some sort of future from which he regresses down memory lane to observe some distant ancestor of his, this seems like a bit to much mixed up in one movie. They should've stuck to the game concept where things happen in a specific set time line and the assassin order is displayed in accordance with the period which is used in each episode. It's a pity when you take such a rich source material  - that is a treasure trove for any writer or film maker - and you mess it up or come up short. Just very disappointing.

text: Okay, can I politely ask the fans to stop complaining about the song? Your adding nothing new. Everybody has been saying this since the trailer dropped. Not only that but now they want the trailer to have songs like Ezio's Family to be playing. You know what a stupid move that would be for the creators? First of all have you ever seen any Assassins Creed video game cinematic trailer ever use that song or any previous themes of any of the games? No! They play songs by Woodkid, or Lorde, or artists that nobody has ever heard of. Now think about this. The trailers song is meant to give hype. And I think this song works. But what I would have preferred instead was for there not to be any rapping in the trailer. That would've made it a lot better. And by the way, stop bitching about how the song "ruined" the trailer. Please! It's still an exciting and hype trailer! Now I couldn't agree more, I wish they would have chosen a different song. But please don't make such a big deal out of it.

text: Everyone is bashing the music, and rightfully so, it sucks. However, no one is addressing why they chose it. Fantasy/medieval/epic/sword and sandals movies are dead. The general mainstream audience is no longer awed as they once were seeing historical combat on the big screen. They already got all you gaming nerds and fantasy fans in the theater, that is a given no matter what they do. So the trailer is not for any of you. What they are trying to do is market to this kardashian, bachelor, snapchat, instagram, lady gaga whatever generation and trick as many of these zombies as possible into buying tickets. This is why it aired on kimmel and why you see modern music in so many period trailers.

A trailer is what gets you interested in a film and if you see music that doesn't fit with the type and genre of the film in the film trailer of course you are not going to be happy and also disappointed! Instrumental music composed by Thomas Bergerson etc would of fit this trailer better! Music is important, it gives so much emotion. text: This movie looks like it's doing everything right (solid director, great cast, practical effects when they can, a historical time period/setting that parallels the Crusades (Reconquista and Crusades were essentially on opposite sides of the Mediterranean) enough to stand alone, etc.), but the thing that REALLY scares me is the screenwriters; Bill Collage & Adam Cooper (who also wrote the flops; "Tower Heist", "Transporter: Refueled", "The Divergent Series: Allegiant", and "Exodus: Gods and Kings").  Many people underestimate that the screenwriters are one of the most (if not THE most) important part of the movie as they provide the story, plot, and dialogue that makes the foundation of the the movie, and a bad foundation will cause the whole building to fall apart regardless of how good the rest of the material is.  Please, Please, PLEASE! Don't suck!!!

author: Stephen Curry

text: En 1492, Andalucía, durante la guerra de Granada, Aguilar de Nerha (Michael Fassbender) es aceptado en la Hermandad de Asesinos. Está asignado a proteger al príncipe Ahmed (Kemaal Deen-Ellis) de Granada de los Caballeros Templarios. En 1986, el adolescente Callum "Cal" Lynch (Angus Brown) encuentra a su madre Mary (Essie Davis) asesinada por su padre, Joseph (Brian Gleeson), un Asesino moderno. Hombres armados liderados por Alan Rikkin (Jeremy Irons), CEO de Abstergo Industries de los Templarios, llegan para capturar a Joseph, quien convence a su hijo para que escape.  En 2016, un adulto Cal (Michael Fassbender) es condenado a muerte por asesinar a un chulo, pero su ejecución es falsificada por Abstergo Industries, que luego lo lleva a su centro de investigación en Madrid. Le dicen que los templarios están buscando el Fruto del Edén para eliminar la violencia usando el código de Fruto para controlar el libre albedrío de la humanidad. Sophia (Marion Cotillard), la hija de Alan y el científico principal, revela que Cal es un descendiente de Aguilar, la última persona que se confirmó que estaba en posesión del Fruto. Ella pone a Cal en el Animus, una máquina que le permite revivir (y los científicos observar) los recuerdos genéticos de Aguilar, para que Abstergo pueda aprender lo que hizo con el Fruto.  En España del siglo XV, Aguilar y su compañera María (Ariane Labed) son desplegados para rescatar a Ahmed, quien ha sido secuestrado por el Gran Maestro Templario Tomás de Torquemada (Javier Gutiérrez), para coaccionar al padre de Ahmed, el sultán Muhammad XII (Khalid Abdalla), para que entregue el Fruto. Aguilar y María interceptan a los templarios, pero son vencidos y capturados por Ojeda (Hovik Keuchkerian), el ejecutor de Torquemada. Cal es rápidamente sacado del Animus por Sophia.
author: Stephen Curry

text: El Animus (Animi en plural) fue una máquina de realidad virtual creada por la Primera Civilización, usada para leer la memoria genética de un sujeto y proyectarla a una pantalla externa en tres dimensiones. Fue redescubierta por Industrias Abstergo en el siglo XX, que usó la máquina para recoger datos de la memoria genética de los sujetos de prueba del Proyecto Animus.
